Problem Statement¶

The objective of this report is to conduct univariate linear regression analysis using the California Housing Prices dataset. The main focus of this analysis is to identify how the median income, population, and the number of households individually influence the median house value. The insights gained here can guide the various stakeholders in making informed decisions about housing and urban development.¶

Observations:

Overall the dataset exhibits significant variability in each variable. Potential outliers are noticeable in median income, population, and number of households. So the next step would be to visualize the distribution of each variable which will provide valuable insights for further analysis and modeling.

Visualization¶

median house value vs. median income¶

In [420]:
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x="median_income", y="median_house_value" , hue="latitude").set(title='Median House Value vs. Median Income')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Observations :

  • The plot shows a strong positive relationship between median income and median house value
  • There is clustering of data points at the lower end of x and y axes which could indicate that the large no. of datapoints fall into lower median income and lower median house value
  • The plot also shows that the median_house_value is capped at 500,001. This could potentially affect the analysis because the actual house values might be significantly higher than this cap.

median house value vs. population¶

In [421]:
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x="population", y="median_house_value" , hue="median_house_value", palette="crest").set(title='Median House Value vs. Population')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Observations :

  • The scatter plot doesn't show a very strong relationship between median house value and population. Datapoints are scattered all over.
  • There are a few data points with a high population but relatively low median house value which could be potential outliers
  • There is concentration of data points towards the lower population and lower median house value. This could indicate that the areas with lower populations tend to have lower median house values.
  • The plot also shows that the median_house_value is capped at 500,001. This could potentially affect the analysis because the actual house values might be significantly higher than this cap.

  • There is a concentration of data points towards the lower no of households and lower median house value.
  • The plot also shows that the median_house_value is capped at 500,001. This could potentially affect the analysis because the actual house values might be significantly higher than this cap.

Linear Regression¶

median_income_model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
median_income_model.fit(X=df[["median_income"]], y =df[["median_house_value"]])

Conclusion¶

The best fit among the three models is the one using 'Median Income' as the predictor variable as it has the lowest MAE and MSE. The equation of the line of best fit for the 'Median Income' model is y = 41793.85x + 45085.58 where 41793.85 is the slope and 45085.58 is the intercept

Also observed that the 'Population' model has a negative slope which suggest an inverse relationship between population and median house value.
